### Markdown to HTML Conversion Function

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string &markdown) {
    // Define regular expressions for common Markdown elements
    std::regex headingRegex(R"(# {1,6}(.*?))");
    std::regex linkRegex(R"(\[(.*?)\]\((.*?)\))");
    std::regex imageRegex(R"(\!\[(.*?)\]\((.*?)\))");

    // Replace heading levels with HTML <h1> - <h6> tags
    std::smatch match;
    std::string result;
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, match, headingRegex)) {
        int level = match.str(0).size() - 1;
        std::string headingContent = match.str(1);
        result += std::string(level < 6 ? "<h" + std::to_string(level) + ">" : "<h6>") + headingContent + "</h" + std::to_string(level) + ">";
        markdown.erase(match.position(), match.length());
    }

    // Replace links with HTML <a> tags
    std::regex_replace(markdown, linkRegex, "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    // Replace images with HTML <img> tags
    std::regex_replace(markdown, imageRegex, "<img src=\"$2\" alt=\"$1\">");

    // Return the resulting HTML string
    return result + markdown;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Heading 1\n## Heading 2\n### Heading 3\n[Link Text](https://example.com)\n![Image Alt Text](https://example.com/image.jpg)";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);

    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

### Explanation

- The function `markdownToHtml` takes a `std::string` containing Markdown-formatted text as an argument.
- It uses regular expressions to find common Markdown elements like headings, links, and images.
- It replaces these elements with their corresponding HTML tags.
- The function returns the resulting HTML-formatted text.

### Example

The `main` function demonstrates the usage of the `markdownToHtml` function. It converts a sample Markdown text into HTML and prints the result.

